            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Include original data, proprietary research, expert quotes, unique case studies, or novel analytical frameworks. Documenting your own test results counts. The essential element: state something no other ranking page currently expresses. A single genuine data point can outweigh thousands of words of repackaged content.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does word count affect information gain?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Not directly. A 500-word article with genuine unique insight outperforms a 3,000-word article repeating common knowledge. Length helps only when every added section contributes genuinely new value. Google measures novelty per statement, not words per page.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What does not count as information gain?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Rephrasing existing points, adding extra subheadings without new substance, padding word count, or replicating what the top 10 results already say. Information gain requires genuine novelty — a claim, number, or perspective that doesn't appear in competing pages.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How does information gain relate to E-E-A-T?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>They are complementary signals. E-E-A-T signals who created the content and whether they have real experience. Information gain signals whether the content itself adds something new. The strongest pages demonstrate both: an experienced author sharing genuinely original insights unavailable elsewhere.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

